--

“The app feels slow.”
Nobody said this directly. Nobody filed a ticket. Nobody sent an angry email.
But I could see it in the data.
Our Lighthouse performance score was sitting at 54. Not terrible. Not good. The kind of score that makes you wince and say “we’ll fix it later.” Our initial JavaScript bundle was 2.4MB. On a decent laptop on WiFi, the app took 4.1 seconds to become interactive. On a mid-range Android phone on 4G — the kind of device a significant portion of our users actually had — we were looking at 9+ seconds before anything worked.
Users were experiencing our “loading” spinner for almost ten seconds.
I finally ran the actual numbers. <cite index=”43–1">Google’s research found that 53% of mobile users abandon a page that takes more than 3 seconds to load.</cite>
53%. More than half. Gone before the app even finished loading.
That Tuesday afternoon I blocked my calendar for three days and dove in.
The result: 2.4MB → 710KB. Lighthouse performance score 54 → 91. Time to interactive 4.1s → 1.3s.
No features removed. No functionality cut. No rewrites.
Just finding the waste and eliminating it, one decision at a time.
Here’s exactly what I did.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Generated by AuthorStep 0: Seeing the Problem (Bundle Analysis)
You can’t fix what you can’t see. The first thing I did was install webpack-bundle-analyzer and actually look at what was in our bundle.
npm install --save-dev webpack-bundle-analyzer source-map-explorerFor Create React App / Vite projects:
# Build first
npm run build# Then analyze
npx source-map-explorer 'build/static/js/*.js'
The visualization was… eye-opening. There were libraries I didn’t even know were in the project. Dependencies of dependencies, brought in transitively. A charting library that took up 340KB and was only used on one admin-only page. A date formatting library that shipped 300KB+ even though we were only using three functions from it.
This is always where I start. Not with “let me optimize React.lazy imports.” With “what the hell is actually in here?”
Time invested: 30 minutes. Insight gained: everything.
Fix 1: Stop Sending Everything on First Load (Route-Based Code Splitting)
Bundle reduction: ~680KB from initial load
This was the biggest single win and also the most obvious one in hindsight.
Our app had a typical SaaS structure: dashboard, reports page, settings, admin panel, billing page, onboarding flow. All of this was bundled together and sent to the user on first load.
A user logging in to check the dashboard was downloading the entire admin panel, the onboarding flow, the billing page — everything. Whether they’d ever visit those pages or not.
The fix: Load each route’s code only when the user actually navigates to it.
Before:
import Dashboard from './pages/Dashboard';
import Reports from './pages/Reports';
import Settings from './pages/Settings';
import AdminPanel from './pages/AdminPanel';
import Billing from './pages/Billing';
import Onboarding from './pages/Onboarding';function App() {
return (
<Routes>
<Route path="/dashboard" element={<Dashboard />} />
<Route path="/reports" element={<Reports />} />
<Route path="/settings" element={<Settings />} />
<Route path="/admin" element={<AdminPanel />} />
<Route path="/billing" element={<Billing />} />
<Route path="/onboarding" element={<Onboarding />} />
</Routes>
);
}
After:
import { lazy, Suspense } from 'react';
const Dashboard = lazy(() => import('./pages/Dashboard'));
const Reports = lazy(() => import('./pages/Reports'));
const Settings = lazy(() => import('./pages/Settings'));
const AdminPanel = lazy(() => import('./pages/AdminPanel'));
const Billing = lazy(() => import('./pages/Billing'));
const Onboarding = lazy(() => import('./pages/Onboarding'));
function App() {
return (
<Suspense fallback={<PageLoader />}>
<Routes>
<Route path="/dashboard" element={<Dashboard />} />
<Route path="/reports" element={<Reports />} />
<Route path="/settings" element={<Settings />} />
<Route path="/admin" element={<AdminPanel />} />
<Route path="/billing" element={<Billing />} />
<Route path="/onboarding" element={<Onboarding />} />
</Routes>
</Suspense>
);
}Six lines changed. The webpack bundler now creates separate chunks for each route. Users download the dashboard code when they visit the dashboard. They download reports code when they visit reports. The admin panel code? Never downloaded if they never visit admin.
What this actually did to our bundle:
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Before: all of that on first load = 780KB just for routes.
After: 94KB on first load, rest deferred.
One thing I added: prefetching for routes the user is likely to visit next. When they hover over the “Reports” nav item, we start fetching that chunk in the background:
// Prefetch on hover - download before user clicks
const prefetchReports = () => import('./pages/Reports');
<NavItem
to="/reports"
onMouseEnter={prefetchReports}
>
Reports
</NavItem>By the time they click, the chunk is already downloaded. Zero perceived latency.
Fix 2: Ditch Moment.js (The 300KB Time Thief)
Bundle reduction: ~280KB
I opened the bundle analyzer and saw moment taking up 296KB gzipped. Including locale files for 15 languages we weren't using.
We were using moment for exactly four things:

• Formatting dates in the dashboard

• Calculating time ago (“3 hours ago”)

• Parsing API response dates

• Adding/subtracting days in the date picker
That’s it. Four functions. We were shipping 296KB to do four things that day.js does in 2KB.
<cite index=”56–1">Day.js is immutable, 2KB gzipped, and mirrors Moment’s API closely enough to make migration a diff rather than a rewrite.</cite> Moment.js’s own maintainers now recommend against using it in new projects.
The migration:
npm uninstall moment
npm install dayjs// Before
import moment from 'moment';
const formatted = moment(date).format('MMM D, YYYY');
const timeAgo = moment(date).fromNow();
const nextWeek = moment().add(7, 'days').toDate();// After - API is nearly identical
import dayjs from 'dayjs';
import relativeTime from 'dayjs/plugin/relativeTime';
dayjs.extend(relativeTime);
const formatted = dayjs(date).format('MMM D, YYYY');
const timeAgo = dayjs(date).fromNow();
const nextWeek = dayjs().add(7, 'days').toDate();
Migration time: 2 hours. Bundle savings: 280KB.
If you prefer tree-shaking and functional style, date-fns is also excellent — you import only the functions you use, so the bundle impact is proportional to your actual usage.
// date-fns approach - only pay for what you use
import { format, formatDistanceToNow, addDays } from 'date-fns';const formatted = format(date, 'MMM d, yyyy');
const timeAgo = formatDistanceToNow(date, { addSuffix: true });
const nextWeek = addDays(new Date(), 7);
Either way, moment.js has to go. There is no scenario in 2026 where shipping 296KB for date formatting is acceptable.
Fix 3: Fix Lodash Imports (The Tree-Shaking Trap)
Bundle reduction: ~65KB
This one is subtle. Lodash is everywhere. It’s useful. But there’s a right and wrong way to import it.
The wrong way (ships ALL of lodash):
import _ from 'lodash'; // Ships the entire 70KB lodash library
const grouped = _.groupBy(users, 'department');
const unique = _.uniqBy(items, 'id');The right way (ships only what you use):
import groupBy from 'lodash/groupBy'; // Ships ~2KB
import uniqBy from 'lodash/uniqBy'; // Ships ~2KBOr even better for modern JavaScript:
// Native JS equivalents (0KB) - ES2024+
const grouped = Object.groupBy(users, u => u.department);
const unique = [...new Map(items.map(i => [i.id, i])).values()];I ran a search across the codebase for import _ from 'lodash' and import { ... } from 'lodash'. Found 11 files importing the whole library. Changed all of them to per-function imports or replaced with native JS where the function was simple enough.
Quick audit:
# Find all lodash imports in your project
grep -r "from 'lodash'" src/ --include="*.ts" --include="*.tsx"
grep -r "require('lodash')" src/ --include="*.ts" --include="*.tsx"If that list is long, add the babel-plugin-lodash or lodash-webpack-plugin to automatically transform barrel imports into per-function imports at build time.
Fix 4: Lazy Load Heavy Components (Not Just Routes)
Bundle reduction: ~220KB from initial load
Route-level code splitting is obvious. Component-level code splitting is where things get interesting.
We had several heavy components that weren’t routes:

• A rich text editor (used only in one content creation form)

• A data visualization chart (used only on the analytics page)

• A PDF preview component (used only when viewing reports)

• A code syntax highlighter (used only in documentation sections)
All of these were imported at the top of their parent files and bundled into the initial load, even though most users never triggered the code paths that rendered them.
Before:
// analytics.tsx
import { HeavyChart } from '../components/HeavyChart'; // 180KB
import { PDFPreview } from '../components/PDFPreview'; // 95KB
function AnalyticsPage() {
const [showChart, setShowChart] = useState(false);
const [showPDF, setShowPDF] = useState(false); return (
<div>
{showChart && <HeavyChart data={data} />}
{showPDF && <PDFPreview url={pdfUrl} />}
</div>
);
}
After:
// analytics.tsx
const HeavyChart = lazy(() => import('../components/HeavyChart'));
const PDFPreview = lazy(() => import('../components/PDFPreview'));function AnalyticsPage() {
const [showChart, setShowChart] = useState(false);
const [showPDF, setShowPDF] = useState(false);
return (
<div>
<Suspense fallback={<ChartSkeleton />}>
{showChart && <HeavyChart data={data} />}
</Suspense>
<Suspense fallback={<Spinner />}>
{showPDF && <PDFPreview url={pdfUrl} />}
</Suspense>
</div>
);
}
The chart and PDF preview only download when the user clicks the button to show them. For users who never click those buttons — the majority — we never ship that code.
Rule of thumb I use: any component over 30KB that’s not shown on initial render is a candidate for lazy loading.
To find candidates quickly:
# After npm run build, look for large chunks
ls -la build/static/js/ | sort -k5 -rn | head -20The ones listed there that aren’t loaded on first paint are your targets.
Fix 5: Replace Heavy npm Packages with Lighter Alternatives
Bundle reduction: ~180KB
This one requires actually looking at what packages are in your project and asking “is there a lighter option?”
Here’s what I found and replaced:
axios → native fetch
We were using axios for API calls. Nothing wrong with axios, but it’s 13KB and we weren’t using any of its advanced features (interceptors we weren’t using, request cancellation we hadn’t set up).
// Before - 13KB
import axios from 'axios';
const data = await axios.get('/api/users').then(res => res.data);// After - 0KB (native)
const data = await fetch('/api/users').then(res => res.json());
We wrapped fetch in a thin utility that added our auth headers and error handling. ~40 lines. Replaced axios entirely.
react-icons (entire library) → specific icon imports
This one was painful to discover. We had import { FiUser, FiSettings } from 'react-icons/fi' scattered throughout the codebase — which sounds fine, but the way we'd initially imported it was actually pulling in far more than intended.
// What we had in some files - pulls in more than expected
import { FiUser } from 'react-icons';// What it should be - per-icon-set imports only
import { FiUser } from 'react-icons/fi';
import { MdDashboard } from 'react-icons/md';
Audit your icon imports. They’re a common source of unexpected bundle bloat.
A useful reference: Check bundlephobia.com before adding any new npm package. It shows you the gzipped bundle size and whether the package is tree-shakeable. Takes 30 seconds and has saved me from adding bloated packages dozens of times.
Fix 6: Enable Proper Tree Shaking (The Config Fix)
Bundle reduction: ~85KB
